headline.main: MY LIFE AS A WRONG NUMBER

results.snippet: A LOT OF PEOPLE RECOGnize my name. Some, in fact, do more than that; they seek me out by mail or, more often, by telephone. They confess admiration for my work, then ask me for favors. I try to accept their praise. However, I can't do anything for...
results.lead_paragraph: A LOT OF PEOPLE RECOGnize my name. Some, in fact, do more than that; they seek me out by mail or, more often, by telephone. They confess admiration for my work, then ask me for favors. I try to accept their praise. However, I can't do anything for these people. The guy they want is someone else, a photographer known for his elegant fashion work, who also lives in New York. I found out about him several years ago. I was just out of graduate school, a teacher in a private high school living on a teacher's salary in Manhattan, which is to say I had a roommate. We split expenses. He paid for the heat; I took care of the phone, so it was listed in my name. A common enough arrangement, and a pretty good one. What got on our nerves were the phone calls for the other Bruce Weber. My roommate and I were new in town at the time. Not many people knew us, much less about us, so the phone's ringing was a relatively big deal. The potential of it - a job offer, an inheritance, a girl. When you were that young, you still think a phone call can change your life. Most of the time, though (I took half a dozen phone calls a week myself), it was: ''Is this Bruce Weber, the photographer?''

results.lead_paragraph: Monday Congress meets in joint session at noon to count the electoral ballots and formally complete the process of electing the President and Vice President. Although both Houses will then be in recess until Inauguration Day, Jan. 21, the new Senate majority leader, Bob Dole of Kansas, has announced plans to meet this week with Republican legislators and Administration officials in an attempt to come up with a budget and deficit-reduction package. The judicial branch of the Federal Government will resume work today as the Supreme Court returns from a four-week recess. And at the White House, it looks like a quiet few days for President Reagan as his press office has announced no public engagements for this week. Attention no doubt is being focused on the budget process and on Geneva, where Secretary of State George P. Shultz is meeting today and tomorrow with Foreign Minister Andrei A. Gromyko of the Soviet Union in an effort to restart the arms control negotiations.

headline.main: U.S.-SOVIET MISSION IN SPACE IS SOUGHT

results.snippet: The United States is prepared to make a high-level overture to the Soviet Union for a simulated space rescue in which American and Russian astronauts would transfer between spacecraft.    The National Aeronautics and Space Administration confirmed...
results.lead_paragraph: The United States is prepared to make a high-level overture to the Soviet Union for a simulated space rescue in which American and Russian astronauts would transfer between spacecraft. The National Aeronautics and Space Administration confirmed today that the proposal could be made as early as this week. A spokesman, Sarah Keegan, said she did not know if it would be brought up in the current arms talks in Geneva between Secretary of State George P. Shultz and the Soviet Foreign Minister, Andrei A. Gromyko.

headline.main: ON THE ROAD TO THE 19TH HOLE

results.snippet: He's been playing golf for so lcng, he claims he washes his golf balls with Epsom salts. He confesses that his swing has been described as that of a polo player without a horse. And he needs scorecards that aren't allergic to erasers. These...
results.lead_paragraph: He's been playing golf for so lcng, he claims he washes his golf balls with Epsom salts. He confesses that his swing has been described as that of a polo player without a horse. And he needs scorecards that aren't allergic to erasers. These one-liners have been teed up from ''Bob Hope's Confessions of a Hooker: My Lifelong Love Affair With Golf,'' soon to be published by Doubleday as a comic antidote for all those tortuous tomes on how to hit the ball slightly straight. Written in collaboration with Dwayne Netland, this book sounds as it should - like a Bob Hope monologue at his Desert Classic in Palm Springs, Calif., where the PGA Tour opened yesterday.

headline.main: DINING A LA CARTE IN THE SPACE SHUTTLE

results.snippet: HOUSTON     REMEMBER the bad old days of space travel, when astronauts had to subsist on pastelike food sucked from toothpaste tubes, graham crackers squashed into cubes and insipid little dried-beef sandwiches they had to rehydrate with their...
results.lead_paragraph: HOUSTON REMEMBER the bad old days of space travel, when astronauts had to subsist on pastelike food sucked from toothpaste tubes, graham crackers squashed into cubes and insipid little dried-beef sandwiches they had to rehydrate with their saliva? Well, all that has changed. During the next mission, tentatively scheduled for Jan. 23, the crew of the space shuttle Discovery will be consuming comparatively normal dishes such as green beans with mushrooms and meatballs with barbecue sauce. Since the mission is primarily a military one, its duration is a secret. Much of the food is bought right off the shelf in groceries in the Houston area and freeze-dried or repackaged. All the space traveler has to do now is float over to the galley, squirt six ounces of water into a food pack, heat and serve. What has made this possible is the realization that scientists' initial apprehensions - particularly the belief that weightlessness would make it difficult to chew and swallow food - were groundless and that space travel requires no special diet. Astronauts require only safe, nutritious fare that is easy to prepare. Indeed, 12 hours before each flight the shuttle is loaded with fresh bananas, oranges, peaches, carrots, celery, bread and the like for the first few days. Since the orbiter has no refrigerator, the astronauts rely on packaged foods later in the flight.

results.lead_paragraph: TIME'S ARROWS: Scientific Attitudes Toward Time. By Richard Morris. 240 pages. Simon & Schuster. $17.95. WHAT is there to say about time except that it never seems to come in the right quantity: for most of us there is either too little of it or too much. There is plenty to say about time, according to Richard Morris, a theoretical physicist who has written five previous books on scientific subjects, including ''Light,'' ''Evolution and Human Nature,'' and ''Dismantling the Universe.''

results.lead_paragraph: PALO ALTO, Calif. Joe Montana had to be in the San Francisco 49ers' locker room. It was, after all, halftime and the quarterback had to be chewing on an orange and watching Coach Bill Walsh diagram a few new plays for the second half. But no, it appeared Joe Montana was at midfield, pretending to be an astronaut. He was wearing a white spacesuit with a rocket attached to his back. With a whoosh, he ascended into the air, zoomed above the field for a few moments and eventually landed near the sideline. Another 30-yard gain. That wasn't Joe Montana, of course. Come to think of it, that couldn't have been him. Joe Montana always lands in the end zone.

results.snippet: Wherever it is going, whatever it is carrying, however long its planned mission, the space shuttle Discovery took off this afternoon on the first flight of American astronauts dedicated exclusively to secret military objectives.    Launching time,...

byline.original: By JOHN NOBLE WILFORD, Special to the New York Times

results.lead_paragraph: Wherever it is going, whatever it is carrying, however long its planned mission, the space shuttle Discovery took off this afternoon on the first flight of American astronauts dedicated exclusively to secret military objectives. Launching time, which had been one of the best-kept secrets of the mission, was 2:50 P.M. The National Aeronautics and Space Administration, complying with the elaborate security rules imposed by the Defense Department, would not disclose even after the fact whether the liftoff came on schedule, but it was clearly visible to spectators at the the press viewing site three miles away. Such information, the Air Force added, might provide important clues as to the identity and purpose of the secret payload in the discovery's cargo bay. Reports About Mission Published reports have described the payload as a 5,000-pound electronic intelligence-gathering satellite capable of monitoring missile tests and intercepting military and diplomatic telecommunications of the Soviet Union. A likely major use of the satellite will be to help warn of Soviet preparations for a nuclear attack on the United States, according to military experts outside the Government. (Page A12.)

byline.original: By WAYNE BIDDLE, Special to the New York Times

results.lead_paragraph: A group of Florida undertakers has joined with a former astronaut in the world's first commercial space venture, with plans to rocket human ashes into an orbit of the Earth. The Celestis Group of Melbourne, Fla., signed a contract last week with Space Services Inc., based in Houston, to fire a payload of cremated human remains into an orbit at 1,900 miles above the earth. Donald K. Slayton, one of the original seven American astronauts, is president of Space Services. He said the mission would cost about $15 million and was scheduled for late 1986 or 1987.

headline.main: INDIA'S UNITY IS CELEBRATED AMID STRAINS

results.snippet: As usual, elephants in billowing satin blankets carried children who had won awards for heroism. Helicopters flew by, showering the delighted crowd with marigold and rose petals. Tribal dancers marched to the music of bells and drums.    Hundreds...
results.lead_paragraph: As usual, elephants in billowing satin blankets carried children who had won awards for heroism. Helicopters flew by, showering the delighted crowd with marigold and rose petals. Tribal dancers marched to the music of bells and drums. Hundreds of thousands of people lined the streets here today as military bands in scarlet uniforms paraded by. Tanks with huge guns were followed by rocket launchers and missiles. A caravan of camels wearing brass anklets carried men in white tunics and red turbans holding semiautomatic rifles.

headline.main: NO MAJOR PROBLEMS REPORTED FOR SHUTTLE

results.snippet: CAPE CANAVERAL, Fla., Jan. 28    The space shuttle Discovery experienced few engineering problems on its three-day secret military mission and survived its fiery descent to earth Sunday without significant damage, the National Aeronautics and Space...
results.lead_paragraph: CAPE CANAVERAL, Fla., Jan. 28 The space shuttle Discovery experienced few engineering problems on its three-day secret military mission and survived its fiery descent to earth Sunday without significant damage, the National Aeronautics and Space Administration announced today. Meanwhile, with the successful performance of the satellite-boosting rocket on the flight, engineering teams here at the Kennedy Space Center pressed ahead with preparations for the next shuttle flight, set for launching Feb. 20. Space agency officials expressed cautious optimism that the Challenger, one of the Discovery's sister ships, would be ready in time for the flight. It is undergoing extensive repair of its heat-shielding tiles, many of which came loose after the Challenger's last flight in October. More than 4,000 of the shuttle's 30,000 tiles have had to be replaced and rebonded to the fuselage.
